{"cursor":"21442","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox military unit |unit_name= Intelligence Support Activity |image=\n|caption= Intelligence Support Activity patch |dates= 1981 |country= United\nStates |allegiance= |branch= United States Army |type= United States Special\nOperations Forces |role= Operational preparation of the battlefield, provides\nHUMINT and SIGINT |size= |command_structure= |current_commander= |garrison=\n|ceremonial_chief= |colonel_of_the_regiment= |nickname= \"The Activity\" |patron=\n|motto= \"Send Me\" or Veritas Omnia Vincula Vincit (\"Truth Overcomes All Bonds\")\n|colors= |march= |mascot= |battles= Operation Winter Harvest Operation\nDesert Storm Operation Gothic Serpent Operation Enduring Freedom Operation Iraqi Freedom |anniversaries= }} The 'United States Army\nIntelligence Support Activity' ('USAISA'), frequently shortened to 'Intelligence\nSupport Activity' or 'ISA', and nicknamed 'The Activity' is a Tier-One United\nStates Army Special Operations unit originally subordinated to the US Army\nIntelligence and Security Command (INSCOM). It is tasked to collect actionable\nintelligence in advance of missions by other US special operations forces,\nespecially 1st SFOD-D and DEVGRU in counter-terrorist operations.\n\nUSAISA was the official name of the unit from 1981 to 1989; previously it was\nknown as the Field Operations Group (FOG), created in September 1980. In 1989,\nthe then USAISA commander sent a telex \"terminating\" the USAISA term and his\nSpecial Access Program GRANTOR SHADOW, but the unit continued under a series of\ndifferent codenames which are changed every two years; known codenames include\nCENTRA SPIKE, TORN VICTOR, CEMETERY WIND, and GRAY FOX.\n","linknr":373,"url":"Intelligence_Support_Activity","recorded":1362374680,"links":34,"instances":["author","united_states_army","military","newspaper_reporter","united_states"],"pdf":["http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB46/document6.pdf","http